One person has been arrested in this regard. Nazeeran Bano was allegedly manhandled while she was collecting data for the Census &nbsp | &nbspPhoto Credit:&nbspANI Key Highlights She was collecting data for the Economic Census She was allowed to leave only after she convinced the crowd that she was a Muslim like them A woman was also attacked in West Bengal and her house was burned after local villagers thought she was collecting data for the NRC Kota: One person was arrested after some people allegedly obstructed a woman from collecting data for the Economic Census and manhandled her in Rajasthan's Kota district on Wednesday, police said. The woman identified as Nazeeran Bano had gone to conduct a survey regarding Economic census 2019-20 with some other colleagues. However, she was manhandled by people who alleged that the survey was for CAA and snatched her mobile phone and deleted the census data from an App. They snatched my phone and deleted mobile application containing data entry of about 1000 households, she told ANI. According to a report by TOI, Bano was allowed to leave only after she was able to convince the crowd that she was a Muslim like them. Nazeeran Bano, a resident of Friends colony, was allegedly manhandled while she was collecting data for the Census in Brijdham area under Borekheda police station limits, said Station House Officer (SHO) Mahesh Singh adding that she managed to contact her senior officials who rushed to the spot with police. On the basis of Bano's complaint, police registered a case against one Safaaut Ansari under relevant sections of the Indian Penal Code and arrested him for breach of peace, the officer said. This attack comes after a 20-year-old woman identified as Chumki Khatun was targeted by local villagers who suspected she was collecting data for the NRC. The woman's home in Gourabazar village was also set ablaze after which she and her family were forced to take refuge at the local police station. So far, no one has been arrested in this connection. Chumki was working for Google India and Tata's Trusts' digital literacy initiative for rural women, Internet Saathi.
